"n8n-markdown"><div class=3D"_sticky_8tq3j_188"><h2>AI-powered Google Stitc=
h Design Agent via Telegram using MCP and Gemini</h2>
<p>This workflow implements an <strong>AI-powered design and prototyping as=
sistant</strong> that integrates <strong>Telegram</strong>, <strong>Google =
Gemini</strong>, and <strong>Google Stitch (MCP)</strong> to enable convers=
ational UI generation and project management.<br>
&nbsp;</p>
<h3><strong>How it works</strong></h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
This workflow acts as a Telegram-based AI design assistant that uses Google=
 Gemini as an LLM and Google Stitch MCP tools to manage design projects and=
 generate UI screens from natural language. Incoming Telegram messages are =
authorized by user ID and filtered to only run when the <code>/stitch</code=
> command is used. The cleaned user query is passed to an AI agent with con=
versational memory, which analyzes intent and selectively calls Stitch MCP =
functions such as project creation, screen listing, or UI generation. The a=
gent can also use web search when additional context is needed. Responses a=
re converted from Markdown to Telegram-compatible HTML before being sent ba=
ck to the user.<br>
&nbsp;</p>
<h3><strong>Setup steps</strong></h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
Configure Telegram access by setting your Telegram User ID in the authoriza=
tion Code node and ensuring bot credentials are valid for both trigger and =
response nodes. Set up Google Stitch by creating an API key and configuring=
 an HTTP Header Auth credential with <code>X-Goog-Api-Key</code>, which is =
shared across all Stitch MCP tool nodes. Verify credentials for the Google =
Gemini chat model and the Perplexity web search tool if used. After all cre=
dentials are in place, activate the workflow so the Telegram webhook is reg=
istered and the agent can respond to <code>/stitch</code> commands.</p>
